# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
We use 0 for nodes coming from the left and 1 for nodes coming from the right.

Firstly, we declare a function that counts the zigzag path. One thing to notice is that if a node comes from the left and then goes left again, the zigzag path will be 1. If a node comes from the left and goes to the right, the zigzag path count will increase by 1 from the previous count and vice versa.

The "solve" function takes three parameters: "root", which is the treenode, "dir" which determines the direction the nodes are coming from, and "len" which shows the length of the zigzag path until the current node.



# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(N), where N represents the total number of nodes in the tree. This is because we traverse each node precisely once.

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int ans=0;

    void solve(TreeNode* root, int dir, int len){
        if(root==NULL)  
            return;
        ans = max(ans, len);
        if(dir==0){
            // node comes from the left and then goes left again, the zigzag path will be 1.
            solve(root->left, 0, 1);
            // node comes from the left and goes to the right, the zigzag path count will increase by 1 from the previous count.
            solve(root->right, 1, len+1);
        }else{
            // node comes from the right and then goes right again, the zigzag path will be 1.
            solve(root->left, 0, len+1);
            // node comes from the right and goes to the left, the zigzag path count will increase by 1 from the previous count.
            solve(root->right, 1, 1);
        }
    }

    int longestZigZag(TreeNode* root) {
        solve(root->left, 0, 1);
        solve(root->right, 1, 1);
        return ans;
    }
};
```

