# Intuition
The one way that comes to mind is to find all possible paths but with given nodes can as much as $$10 ^ 4$$ this solution goes in n$$O(n ^2)$$
So intuition was to optimize this approach. 
To optimize we can do:
1. keep track of know length and calculate the max length in one traversal
2. reduce the unnecessary paths (as valid paths are only zigzags so we can eliminate non-zigzag paths)
3. eliminate the calculation of subpaths as parent paths already are bigger than subpath (implies function strictly follows zigzag path)

# Approach
1. create a function that can traverse the tree in the zigZag pattern (recursive functions work in case of trees) 
2. maintain a global variable max and update it at every end of each path (i.e. where root == null)
3. for every node start a new calculation for the opposite direction with length 0 (this will calculate strictly the opposite direction as a path in the same direction, starting a calculation from current node will be a subpath of the already calculated path)

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
In this approach each node is visited only once so time complexity $$O(n)$$

- Space complexity:
$$O(n)$$

# Code
